Bionic Eye Systems: Comprehensive Technical & Clinical Overview
Introduction
A bionic eye (visual prosthesis) is a neuroprosthetic system designed to restore partial visual perception by converting visual information into electrical signals that stimulate the visual pathway.
Biological Vision Pipeline
Light → Retina (rods & cones) → Retinal ganglion cells → Optic nerve → Visual cortex (V1). Signals are encoded as discrete action potentials using rate coding.
Neural Encoding Principles
Visual intensity is encoded as pulse frequency, not amplitude. Prosthetic systems convert image intensity into pulse trains that mimic biological firing patterns.
Stimulation Targets
Retina (epiretinal, subretinal, suprachoroidal), Optic nerve (experimental), Visual cortex (V1).
Australian Bionic Eye Projects
1. Suprachoroidal Retinal Prosthesis (Bionic Vision Technologies)
2. Gennaris Cortical Prosthesis (Monash Vision Group)
System Pipeline
Camera → Visual Processing Unit (edge detection, contrast enhancement, downsampling) → Electrode stimulation → Phosphenes.
Why Optic Nerve Stimulation Is Difficult
Loss of spatial selectivity, axonal cross-talk, encoding mismatch, limited plasticity.
Cortical Stimulation Challenges
Resolution bottleneck, retinotopic variability, phosphene instability, invasiveness.
Current Steering
Virtual electrode creation using differential current to improve resolution.
Future Directions
AI-based encoding, optical cortical stimulation, predictive neural writing.
